{"title_page": "The Ritz-Carlton, Hong Kong", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{use Hong Kong English|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox hotel\n| hotel_name         = The Ritz-Carlton, Hong Kong\n| image              = File:International Commerce Centre 201408.jpg\n| caption            = The Ritz-Carlton, Hong Kong is on the top 16 floors of the [[International Commerce Centre]]\n| location           = [[International Commerce Centre]], [[West Kowloon]]<br />Hong Kong\n| pushpin_map        = \n| coordinates        =\n| opening_date       = {{start date|2011|03|29|df=y}}\n\n| closing_date       =\n| developer          = [[Sun Hung Kai Properties]]\n| operator           = [[Ritz-Carlton Hotel Company]]\n| owner              = Sun Hung Kai Properties\n| number_of_restaurants = 3\n| number_of_rooms    = 312\n| number_of_suites   =\n| floor_area         =\n| floors             = 17\n| parking            =\n| website            = [http://www.ritzcarlton.com/en/Properties/HongKong/ The Ritz-Carlton, Hong Kong official website]\n| footnotes          =\n}}\n'''The Ritz-Carlton, Hong Kong''' ({{zh|t=\u9999\u6e2f\u9e97\u601d\u5361\u723e\u9813\u9152\u5e97}}) is a [[Ritz-Carlton Hotel Company]] [[Hotel rating|five-star hotel]], located on the top floors of the [[International Commerce Centre]], [[West Kowloon]], [[Hong Kong]].\n\nOffering 312 rooms, it occupies the 102nd to 118th floors of the [[Sun Hung Kai Properties]]-owned International Commerce Centre, was the world's highest [[hotel]] from 2011-2019 (currently surpassed by [[Rosewood Hotels & Resorts|Rosewood]] Guangzhou located on the top floors of the [[Guangzhou CTF Finance Centre]]).\nThe hotel features both a bar (called Ozone) and a pool located on the 118th floor, which are the highest [[Bar (establishment)|bar]] and [[swimming pool]] in the world, at 484 metres (1,588&nbsp;ft) above ground level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnngo.com/hong-kong/visit/ritz-2-017129 |title=The Ritz-Carlton Hong Kong: The world's highest hotel opens |date=29 March 2011|publisher=cnngo.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111209061213/http://www.cnngo.com/hong-kong/visit/ritz-2-017129|archivedate=2011-12-09}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Ritz-Carlton, Hong Kong was formerly located at [[Central, Hong Kong]] where it operated from 1993 to 2008.<ref>Press release (undated). [https://web.archive.org/web/20100106150810/http://corporate.ritzcarlton.com/en/Press/Properties/HongKong/Releases/Closure.htm \"The Ritz-Carlton, Hong Kong Will Cease Operations January 1, 2008, Future Properties Now Under Development in Macau and Kowloon\"] (archive). [[The Ritz-Carlton Hotel Company]].  Retrieved 12 August 2014.</ref> It reopened at [[International Commerce Centre]] for business on 29{{nbsp}}March 2011.<ref name=\"opens\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cnngo.com/hong-kong/visit/ritz-2-017129 |title=The Ritz-Carlton Hong Kong: The World's Highest Hotel Opens \u2013  Almost 500 Meters Above Ground and Offering a Very Cozy Lap of Luxury, the Newest Ritz-Carlton Certainly Impresses |date=29 March 2011|author= Li, Zoe |publisher= [[CNN]] | accessdate = 12 August 2014}}</ref> Its interior lighting was designed by British lighting designer [[Sally Storey]].<ref name=\"Upscale\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/usa/upscale-living-magazine/20180409/281517931696151|title=Sally Storey, Lighting up the Luxury World|last=West|first=Angela Sara|date=April 9, 2018|work=Upscale Living|accessdate=2019-10-04}}</ref>\n\n==Features==\nThe {{convert|366|m2|sqft|abbr=on|disp=or}} Presidential Suite is on the 117th floor.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Ritz-Carlton, Hong Kong: Presidential Suite - A sneak peek |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/the-ritz-carlton-hong-kong-presidential-suite-a-sneak-peek-2011-12|work=Business Insider |date=10 December 2011 |accessdate=12 January 2018}}</ref> The hotel's arrival lobby is on the 9th floor where guests are greeted by receptionists and taken to express elevators.  The express elevators take guests {{convert|425|m|ft|abbr=on}} above the ground in 50 seconds to the main lobby on the 103rd floor. Guest keycards are required to use the hotel elevators to access the hotel rooms on floors 104\u2013117 and the swimming pool and gym on floor 118.  An exclusive club lounge for guests staying in club rooms and suites is located on floor 116 along with the spa.\n\n==Restaurants==\nThree restaurants, Tosca (an Italian restaurant), Chinese restaurant [[Tin Lung Heen]] are located one floor below reception on floor 102, while CAF\u00c9 103 is on floor 103.\n\nTin Lung Heen has been given two Michelin stars.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/10/31/travel/michelin-guide-hong-kong-macau-2015/|title=Michelin: Hong Kong 'undisputed leader' in international cuisine|author=Maggie Hiufu Wong|date=3 November 2014|publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref>\n\nTosca is presided by two star Michelin chef [[Pino Lavarra]]. Tosca was given one Michelin star only eight months after Chef Pino took over as director.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/chef-pino-sees-red-tosca-161130635.html|title=Chef Pino Sees Red at Tosca The Ritz-Carlton, Hong Kong|publisher=Yahoo|date=5 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Occupancy==\nThe hotel is targeting a 60% occupancy rate.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ritzcarlton.com/en/Properties/HongKong/Information/Default.htm | publisher=The Ritz-Carlton, Hong Kong | title=Hotel Information | accessdate=14 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:The Ritz-Carlton Hong Kong Level 7 Open Area.jpg|Level 7 open area\nFile:The Ritz-Carlton Hong Kong Outside Parking Area.jpg|Outside parking area\nFile:The Ritz-Carlton Hong Kong Level 103 Lobby.jpg|Lobby on 103rd floor\nFile:The Ritz-Carlton Hong Kong The Lounge & Bar.jpg| The Lounge & Bar\nFile:The Ritz-Carlton Hong Kong Tin Lung Heen View from 103.jpg|Tin Lung Heen Chinese Restaurant\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Architecture|Hong Kong}}\n* [[Architecture of Hong Kong]]\n* [[List of hotels: Countries H#Hong Kong|List of hotels in Hong Kong]]\n* [[List of tallest hotels in the world]]\n* [[List of tallest voluntarily demolished buildings]]\n* [[Sky100]], a 360-degree indoor observation deck on the 100th floor of the [[International Commerce Centre]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|The Ritz-Carlton Hong Kong|Ritz-Carlton Hong Kong, Kowloon}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.cnngo.com/hong-kong/wide-eye-591731#ixzz1FyQlsEV5|title=High at the Ritz: Unrivalled Views at the World's Tallest Hotel \u2013  We Managed to Survive the Incredible Vertigo Inspired by the Sky-High, Panoramic Vistas at the Yet-to-Open Ritz Carlton Hong Kong \u2013  Just |date=11 August 2010|author = Li, Zoe |publisher = [[CNN]] | accessdate = 12 August 2014}}\n\n{{Ritz-Carlton}}\n{{Hotels in Hong Kong}}\n\n{{coord|22.3034|114.1602|display=t}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ritz-Carlton, Hong Kong}}\n[[Category:2011 establishments in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Hotel buildings completed in 2011]]\n[[Category:Hotels established in 2011]]\n[[Category:The Ritz-Carlton Hotel Company|Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Skyscraper hotels in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Sun Hung Kai Properties]]\n[[Category:West Kowloon]]\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{use Hong Kong English|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox hotel\n| hotel_name         = The Ritz-Carlton, Hong Kong\n| image              = File:International Commerce Centre 201408.jpg\n| caption            = The Ritz-Carlton, Hong Kong is on the top 16 floors of the [[International Commerce Centre]]\n| location           = [[International Commerce Centre]], [[West Kowloon]]<br />Hong Kong\n| pushpin_map        = \n| coordinates        =\n| opening_date       = {{start date|2011|03|29|df=y}}\n\n| closing_date       =\n| developer          = [[Sun Hung Kai Properties]]\n| operator           = [[Ritz-Carlton Hotel Company]]\n| owner              = Sun Hung Kai Properties\n| number_of_restaurants = 3\n| number_of_rooms    = 312\n| number_of_suites   =\n| floor_area         =\n| floors             = 17\n| parking            =\n| website            = [http://www.ritzcarlton.com/en/Properties/HongKong/ The Ritz-Carlton, Hong Kong official website]\n| footnotes          =\n}}\n'''The Ritz-Carlton, Hong Kong''' ({{zh|t=\u9999\u6e2f\u9e97\u601d\u5361\u723e\u9813\u9152\u5e97}}) is a [[Ritz-Carlton Hotel Company]] [[Hotel rating|five-star hotel]], located on the top floors of the [[International Commerce Centre]], [[West Kowloon]], [[Hong Kong]].\n\nOffering 312 rooms, it occupies the 102nd to 118th floors of the [[Sun Hung Kai Properties]]-owned International Commerce Centre, was the world's highest [[hotel]] from 2011-2019 (currently surpassed by [[Rosewood Hotels & Resorts|Rosewood]] Guangzhou located on the top floors of the [[Guangzhou CTF Finance Centre]]).\nThe hotel features both a bar (called Ozone) and a pool located on the 118th floor, which are the highest [[Bar (establishment)|bar]] and [[swimming pool]] in the world, at 484 metres (1,588&nbsp;ft) above ground level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnngo.com/hong-kong/visit/ritz-2-017129 |title=The Ritz-Carlton Hong Kong: The world's highest hotel opens |date=29 March 2011|publisher=cnngo.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111209061213/http://www.cnngo.com/hong-kong/visit/ritz-2-017129|archivedate=2011-12-09}}</ref>\n\n==History==]\nThe Ritz-Carlton, Hong Kong was formerly located at [[Central, Hong Kong]] where it operated from 1993 to 2008.<ref>Press release (undated). [https://web.archive.org/web/20100106150810/http://corporate.ritzcarlton.com/en/Press/Properties/HongKong/Releases/Closure.htm \"The Ritz-Carlton, Hong Kong Will Cease Operations January 1, 2008, Future Properties Now Under Development in Macau and Kowloon\"] (archive). [[The Ritz-Carlton Hotel Company]].  Retrieved 12 August 2014.</ref> It reopened at [[International Commerce Centre]] for business on 29{{nbsp}}March 2011.<ref name=\"opens\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cnngo.com/hong-kong/visit/ritz-2-017129 |title=The Ritz-Carlton Hong Kong: The World's Highest Hotel Opens \u2013  Almost 500 Meters Above Ground and Offering a Very Cozy Lap of Luxury, the Newest Ritz-Carlton Certainly Impresses |date=29 March 2011|author= Li, Zoe |publisher= [[CNN]] | accessdate = 12 August 2014}}</ref> Its interior lighting was designed by British lighting designer [[Sally Storey]].<ref name=\"Upscale\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/usa/upscale-living-magazine/20180409/281517931696151|title=Sally Storey, Lighting up the Luxury World|last=West|first=Angela Sara|date=April 9, 2018|work=Upscale Living|accessdate=2019-10-04}}</ref>\n\n==Features==\nThe {{convert|366|m2|sqft|abbr=on|disp=or}} Presidential Suite is on the 117th floor.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Ritz-Carlton, Hong Kong: Presidential Suite - A sneak peek |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/the-ritz-carlton-hong-kong-presidential-suite-a-sneak-peek-2011-12|work=Business Insider |date=10 December 2011 |accessdate=12 January 2018}}</ref> The hotel's arrival lobby is on the 9th floor where guests are greeted by receptionists and taken to express elevators.  The express elevators take guests {{convert|425|m|ft|abbr=on}} above the ground in 50 seconds to the main lobby on the 103rd floor. Guest keycards are required to use the hotel elevators to access the hotel rooms on floors 104\u2013117 and the swimming pool and gym on floor 118.  An exclusive club lounge for guests staying in club rooms and suites is located on floor 116 along with the spa.\n\n==Restaurants==\nThree restaurants, Tosca (an Italian restaurant), Chinese restaurant [[Tin Lung Heen]] are located one floor below reception on floor 102, while CAF\u00c9 103 is on floor 103.\n\nTin Lung Heen has been given two Michelin stars.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/10/31/travel/michelin-guide-hong-kong-macau-2015/|title=Michelin: Hong Kong 'undisputed leader' in international cuisine|author=Maggie Hiufu Wong|date=3 November 2014|publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref>\n\nTosca is presided by two star Michelin chef [[Pino Lavarra]]. Tosca was given one Michelin star only eight months after Chef Pino took over as director.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/chef-pino-sees-red-tosca-161130635.html|title=Chef Pino Sees Red at Tosca The Ritz-Carlton, Hong Kong|publisher=Yahoo|date=5 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Occupancy==\nThe hotel is targeting a 60% occupancy rate.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ritzcarlton.com/en/Properties/HongKong/Information/Default.htm | publisher=The Ritz-Carlton, Hong Kong | title=Hotel Information | accessdate=14 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:The Ritz-Carlton Hong Kong Level 7 Open Area.jpg|Level 7 open area\nFile:The Ritz-Carlton Hong Kong Outside Parking Area.jpg|Outside parking area\nFile:The Ritz-Carlton Hong Kong Level 103 Lobby.jpg|Lobby on 103rd floor\nFile:The Ritz-Carlton Hong Kong The Lounge & Bar.jpg| The Lounge & Bar\nFile:The Ritz-Carlton Hong Kong Tin Lung Heen View from 103.jpg|Tin Lung Heen Chinese Restaurant\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Architecture|Hong Kong}}\n* [[Architecture of Hong Kong]]\n* [[List of hotels: Countries H#Hong Kong|List of hotels in Hong Kong]]\n* [[List of tallest hotels in the world]]\n* [[List of tallest voluntarily demolished buildings]]\n* [[Sky100]], a 360-degree indoor observation deck on the 100th floor of the [[International Commerce Centre]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|The Ritz-Carlton Hong Kong|Ritz-Carlton Hong Kong, Kowloon}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.cnngo.com/hong-kong/wide-eye-591731#ixzz1FyQlsEV5|title=High at the Ritz: Unrivalled Views at the World's Tallest Hotel \u2013  We Managed to Survive the Incredible Vertigo Inspired by the Sky-High, Panoramic Vistas at the Yet-to-Open Ritz Carlton Hong Kong \u2013  Just |date=11 August 2010|author = Li, Zoe |